				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">The x86 architectures has two address spaces: memory and I/O. Everything you've done so far has been in the memory space, which isn't surprising since it's the more commonly used of the two. The one you're looking at now is the I/O address space.<br /><br />You can only access the I/O space with a few instructions. They are <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">in</tt>, <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">out</tt>, <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">insb</tt>, <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">insw</tt>, <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">outsb</tt>, and <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">outsw</tt>. You'll mostly only want to use <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">in</tt> and <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">out</tt> for now. Those two instructions haven't changed much in the lifespan of the x86 architecture, so even modern resources can teach you how to use them. (Of course, ignore the parts that reference 32-bit anything, since the V33 is 16-bit.)</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

